function minLengthAfterOperations(s) {
    const aCount = s.split('a').length - 1;
    const bCount = s.split('b').length - 1;
    const cCount = s.split('c').length - 1;

    if (aCount % 2 === bCount % 2 && bCount % 2 === cCount % 2) {
        return s.length % 2;
    }
    return (s.length + 1) % 2;
}
```

    The algorithm counts the occurrences of each character ('a', 'b', 'c') in the given string. Then, it checks if the counts are all even or all odd, which means that the count of the three characters has the same parity. In this case, the minimum length of the string after performing the operations would be the length of the string modulo 2. Otherwise, the minimum length would be the length of the string plus 1 modulo 2. This is because one character will always remain after performing the operations if the parities of the character counts aren't the same.

